data.title: Southern Wisconsin grad 'better than' All-American to pace Big Ten volleyball rival's offense
meta_keywords: ncaa division i fbs football teams
data.meta_description: A Madison La Follette grad detoured to Central Michigan and used the transfer portal to land at a popular destination for southern Wisconsin recruits.
data.text:
CHICAGO — A steady pipeline of southern Wisconsin athletes leaving the state for a neighboring Big Ten rival extended to the volleyball court in the offseason.

It’s a great opportunity for Madison La Follette grad Claire Ammeraal, who detoured to Central Michigan before transferring to Iowa in the offseason. The third-year setter is the only Hawkeye at her position with college experience and looks to beat out freshman Jenna Moitzler for the starting job. She walked into a rebuilding Hawkeyes team that went winless in the Big Ten and was 8-24 overall last season. But she’s drawing rave reviews after enrolling in January.

“She's a person that will always be saying hi and wishing you, 'I hope you have the best day,' and say it in the most genuine way,” senior middle hitter Anna Davis said. “She genuinely means it in everything she does, but then when you get on the court with her and get into other aspects, she's competitive and fiery and has this edge to her that she is going to win, she's going to find a way to win. And that's not just on the court, but how she attacks school and in the classroom and even games or random things we'll do outside of volleyball and things like that.”

Wisconsin volleyball has 'sense of urgency' for meshing newcomers with experience

Ammeraal’s confidence has left an impression on Davis. But she also has been selfless in trying to adapt to her hitters and make the transition smooth.

“I think as a pin hitter especially that's what I look for in a setter, somebody that's always willing to take feedback, both directions,” senior middle Michelle Urquhart said. “And she is always the first person in, last person out, willing to work 110% extra mile. So we love her to death, in case you guys didn't know. She is a phenomenal dancer, as well. But she's amazing.”

Ammeraal will be an important piece of Jim Barnes’ rebuild at Iowa, which hasn’t won a Big Ten match since Nov. 26, 2022, when it won in five sets over Michigan State to close the season. The Hawkeyes were winless in the 2023 Big Ten season and finished 8-24 overall. The 6-foot-2 Ammeraal hopes to direct an attack that was among the league’s worst last season. Iowa was last with 13.54 points per set and tied for 12th with a .157 hitting percentage across 20 league games.

2 former Badgers on Olympic team 'adding fuel to my fire' for current Wisconsin volleyball stars

For the confidence Ammeraal has instilled in her teammates, Barnes exudes the same confidence back into her. He said she checked every box when the Hawkeyes were evaluating transfers.

“I told her I've coached an All-American setter that was a lefty, as well, at Baylor, and I said, 'You're better than her. ... You have more ability, more talent than she does,'” Barnes said, speaking about Taylor Barnes, an American Volleyball Coaches Association honorable mention All-American in 2009. “This spring just amplified what (Ammeraal) can do. She'll fill up the stat sheet. She's a major threat. But she's one of the most selfless setters on top of that.”

Ammeraal is coming off a sophomore season that led her to be named second team all-MAC and landed her 10th on the Chippewas’ single-season assists list with 1,080. She played all 119 sets and averaged 9.08 assists, 1.41 kills, and 2.71 digs per set for a 15-15 season.

Her freshman season ended with 33 assists as 20-12 Central Michigan was swept by Xavier in the National Invitational Volleyball Championship. Ammeraal finished the season with 935 assists (8.06 per set). She has five triple-doubles in her career.

While her path isn’t the most direct to Iowa City, Iowa, Ammeraal is one of several players from the Madison area to join the Hawkeyes. It’s a list that includes burgeoning football star Addison Ostrenga (Sun Prairie East) and teammate Jack Dotzier (Waunakee), freshmen basketball players Taylor Stremlow (Verona) and Teagan Mallegni (McFarland), softball pitcher Andrea Jaskowiak (Madison Memorial) and recent Iowa graduates McKenna Warnock (Monona Grove, basketball), Torren Young (Monona Grove, football) and Thomas Hartlieb (Madison Edgewood, football).

Ammeraal was a three-time all-Big Eight Conference pick for the Lancers and the league’s player of the year in 2021.
